The National Emergency Management Agency (NEMA), has distributed food items to 3,936 Internally Displaced Persons (IDPs), in Fofure, St. Theresa and Malkohi camps in Adamawa state. Mr Iliya Midala, Head of Operation Adamawa/Taraba states at the distribution exercise gave the breakdown of benefiting households to include Malkohi 1,434, Fufore 1,974 and St. Theresa 528 camps benefited from the intervention. Iliya said the items distributed are rice, beans, tomato paste, seasoning and salt to the IDPs. The Head of Operation, further said that the exercise was in continuation of efforts to provide succour to the IDPs, in line with the mandate of the minister of humanitarian affairs, disaster management and social development. “The foodstuffs and cocking condiments were distributed through NEMA to address the needs of IDPs affected by the Boko Haram insurgency.” He said under the approval granted by Director General, NEMA, AVM Muhammed Alhaji Muhammed (rtd). IDPs in the state are up to date in their monthly disbursement. Bakura Umar, Leader of the IDPs commended the gesture from the federal government and urged to increase the quantity of the items per household. “NEMA and other supporting ministries and agencies should try to increase the monthly foodstuffs which is currently inadequate. “A 50kg bag of rice, two 25kg of beans and condiments is shared between 12 households, we need more”, he maintained. 